segments.text: Let's get back to your father and if he did or didn't have high school.
I don't believe he did.
I believe that he's, I believe he dropped out of high school in the eighth grade or something like that and started working.
My mother finished high school and her younger sister was a school teacher.
Her first cousin was a school teacher.
So they were, and my mother attended Baylor University
for one year, I think.

So the fascination with education was a little more on my mother's side from an experience standpoint than my father's, but my father did respect it greatly and I guess was insistent that his children go as far as they could because he was denied the opportunity.
Why was he denied the opportunity?
Because the family was poor and he had to go to work?
I believe that's right and of course in those days it wasn't considered to be very essential to finish high school either.
True.
He was a highly intelligent person.
He could earn money with his bookkeeping skills and he just
pretty well could teach himself or learn by experience.
Now did the military aspect of A&M have anything to do with your decision to come here?
No.
It didn't.
And you were influenced by the agricultural aspect, in other words then
You, who became a general, never thought of a military career in high school?
No.
Never thought about going to service school like West Point or anything like that?
No.
Okay.
Not at all.
Okay.
You arrived in 1935?
Yes, fall of 1935.
Oh, your first impressions when you got off that train?
Did you come by the train?
I did, yes.
My brother and I made our first trips together.
by a train coming to Texas A&M.
I was mighty awestruck.
Texas A&M had quite a reputation for hazing freshmen at the time.
I was apprehensive and that was a proper attitude because it was a little traumatic.
Can you describe some of the hazing?
In the first place, I guess it's a little unusual that my brother and I didn't attempt to live together.
He was acquainted with somebody that influenced him to get into the infantry here.
I was influenced by a person from, a couple of people from
from Orange County who were in the artillery and consequently my brother and I never lived together here.
I got over into the F Battery Field Artillery where there were two Orange County people in leadership positions that I replaced from the name of I.B.
Murray and
a person named Nelson who was first sergeant of the artillery battery that I joined.
We were of course strongly disciplined as freshmen and really
Looked after day and night primarily by the sophomores.
We were of course room artillers for upperclassmen.
So Abraham Lincoln didn't free all the slaves.
We did a little slave labor as freshmen at Texas A&M.
What kind of work?
Shining shoes?
Well we shined boots and we swept rooms, made beds.
that sort of orderly type activities as freshmen.
Tell me about the hazing.
Well, if you didn't follow the rules according to somebody's desires, they did sometimes use a board on you.
Of course, there were strong traditions about that, about what stance you'd take and how you'd take that.
It was ironical that then, you know, when somebody gave you a licking with the board, you were obliged to congratulate him for his skill at applying to the board.
It didn't hurt anything.
It's, of course, an experience that one remembers always.

I can't advocate that at all, but still there's no question in my mind that going through again some sacrifices here made you appreciate a whole lot more earning a degree under those circumstances in Texas A&M.
So you thought the hazing and the traditions then were beneficial?
Oh certainly, I sure did.
Were you sorry to see the hazing
from the university?
No, not really.
I think that that was a sign of the times.
In those days, it probably was beneficial, but I expect that the expectations of people changed along the way.
I don't regret at all that we have virtually eliminated hazing, as far as I know absolutely eliminated that type of hazing from Texas A&M.
That was a change that was necessary, desirable.
Can you describe your accommodations?
Well, I was quartered in Goodwin Hall.
in my freshman year.
The room was, of course, very Spartan type, wooden floors, not very good, bunk beds.
The enrollment at Texas A&M had just begun to increase beyond dormitory capacity, so there were, not my freshman year, the following years, there were three in a room.
We did stack the bunk beds.
Of course, a basin in the room, but the toilet facilities were just one floor.
We marched the meals, every meal.
Of course, the freshmen were obliged to
We'd get up at Reveille and assemble together out on the steps of the dormitory and sing the artillery song after the bugle blew.
A real live bugler.
It was distinctly an advantage that everybody wore the uniform because of course
My brother and I didn't have any money, but we looked like everybody else on campus and there were a whole bunch of them like that too.
My brother and I did attempt to find student employment.
But there were some 4,000 students on campus our freshman year, and only about 3,000 of them were working student jobs.
Oh, really?
Really?
Very minimum wages, $0.25, $0.30 an hour.
And we just couldn't, though we'd made a special trip up here six months before we enrolled or so, but we were not able to obtain student employment our freshman year.
Did you eventually become employed?
Yes, a sophomore year.
Both my brother and I were members of the janitor force.
The hardest jobs on the janitor force were sweeping dormitories, so we spent the first year doing that.
And then my junior year, I was a janitor in the very building we're sitting in right now.
When I was reassigned here a couple of years ago, I told them I wasn't so awestruck I'd been assigned to this building before.
I knew the building well.
Then as a senior, I was a janitor foreman of student janitors for this building, Animal Industries Ag Building and Pavilion.
I spent freshman year in Goodwin Hall and then the sophomore year was spent in Law Hall.
It still is functional dormitory.
Then the last two years I was in Miller Hall, which recently of course had been remodeled and recommitted to offices and classrooms.

My brother and I were afforded the opportunity to come to college by a relative of my mother's who was a school teacher in Beaumont and she came from Smith County also and she was an unmarried school teacher
when oil was discovered in East Texas in the early 30s and she obtained some wealth from that and she loaned money to my brother and me to come to college.
We borrowed all of the money it took that we didn't earn as student workers to come to college.
I was more thrifty than my brother, and when we graduated, I owed Miss Leila Jarvis $1,220, and he owed her a little over $1,400.
That's what it said.
The total amount it took for us to go to school for four years, other than what we earned as student workers.
Well, what kind of social life did you have then?
And we had a great social life, to the extent you can with all men.
And of course on the ladies it was a very special occasion.
There were dances on campus in relation to football games and that sort of thing.
The strangest thing to me is there probably weren't
Two dozen automobiles owned by students on the whole campus in most cases.
These were secondhand cars that several people had gone in together to buy when they went to ROTC camp between their junior and senior years.
And of course hitchhiking was all the thing in those days.

We had to travel by catch and ride, so usually my brother and I would, if we had an opportunity to go home on the weekend, we would hitchhike or maybe even ride the bus to Houston for three or four dollars and hitchhike from there to Orange.
So there was a great tradition about hitchhiking around Texas A&M then.
wearing your uniform.
Hitchhiking was mighty easy.
Texans had confidence in Texas Aggies.
I'm sure many of them would pick up people in the Texas Aggie cadet uniform.
Then hitchhiking wasn't against regulations?
Oh no, it wasn't.
and there were strong traditions associated with it.
Sometimes on a weekend you'd go out to the east gate to the campus and you might be number 200 in line.
You wouldn't dare upstream anybody or go further up to catch a ride.
Strong conditions anywhere you went.
There was the Aggie hitchhiking line.
It'd be at a certain place and you took your turn in that line.
No kidding.
Sure, Houston or

Beaumont or wherever there's a certain place you went to get your ads and when you got there you determined where you were in the land and you didn't dare move up or upstream anybody and that sort of thing.
Well that was a fine thing.
How was the food in the dormitories during the depression?
Well I would say that it was abundant
and better than most of us had at home.

Of course there weren't complaints about food but this was family service and of course the freshmen were required to wait on the upperclassmen and give them first shot at everything but after the upperclassmen left the mess hall as we called it then
The freshmen had all the food they wanted on their own table or on tables around there.
Of course, it was one of the sacrifices that the freshmen had to make is that they were not allowed to eat desserts during their first year until right at the end of the year.
Of course, the freshmen had nicknames for all the food.
They called it kush.
You weren't allowed to.
eat any pie or dessert.
The upperclassmen got all that they wanted, food in their share and that of the freshmen.
So it was a great event right toward the end of your freshman year when you were, you had earned your spurs, so to speak, and were allowed to eat kush.
I expect many freshmen did, but they had to do it kind of surreptitiously.
What were some of the things that you liked about the Corps and some of the things that you disliked about the Corps?
Well I liked very much the camaraderie of the Corps, being one of the guys.
and passing the tests, whatever sacrifices you were required to make.
There were 32 of us in my freshman class in my ROTC outfit.
It is macho to be one of the tougher ones.
You could take the hazing, you could take whatever requirements there were without knuckling under.
So there's no question in my mind that that molded character quite a bit.
Then the camaraderie of not only your classmates, but of your military organization.
The F battery field artillery was something special.
Anything you disliked about it?
Anything that bothered you about it at the time?
I really adapted real well to the military and corps life.
I liked it first grade.
You know back in the 1930s American foreign policy was isolationist basically.
While the Japanese and the Germans were very aggressive
We were sticking our head in the sand, and one might say that we were almost anti-militaristic in this country back in the mid-1930s when you were here at A&M.
We only had an army of about 100,000 men.
Did this mood ever appear here at A&M?
No, absolutely not.
We had some real outstanding ROTC instructors.
It's amazing to me how many of those who were captains, majors, right after we got more involved and started expanding the military forces rose right on up to be general officers.
We really had some mighty outstanding
active army people here as ROTC instructors.
Do you remember any that had an influence on your life and what was that influence?
Oh sure.
Who were these people?
Well there was a Colonel O.E.
Beasley who was chief of the artillery branch of ROTC and Captain Lloyd Garrison, a dapper bachelor type.
There were a couple of other artillery instructors.
Right now I'm having a little bit of trouble remembering their names, but all of these were outstanding active army type people.
They were demanding, but fair people.
I don't know.
I'd say they had tremendous influence on my young life.
I thought I'd really gotten somewhere when I got to be a senior.
Colonel Beasley, who was quite a horseman himself, selected me to help him in teaching equitation.
Of course, battery field artillery was a horse-drawn outfit.
Of course, we had cavalry horses and artillery horses on campus.
just west of the railroad, we had stables there.
Of course I'd had quite a bit of previous experience with horses at home.
So I thought it was something mighty special that Colonel Beasley would come by Milner Hall and pick me up and take me down and I could help him teach equitation to sophomore students in ROTC.
It appears that you admired this man.
Oh yes, I did.
Garrison Lieutenant Benny P. Heiser, I remember.
How would you spell that?
He was a H-E-I-S-E-R.
He was a great big sort of heavy set man.
He was a little bit of a clown.
Of course a West Point graduate.
I remember his telling us in ROTC classes that when he was in the 12th Field Artillery of the 2nd Infantry Division of San Antonio, Dizzy Dean was a soldier.
He was a catcher on the baseball team and Dizzy Dean was a pitcher.
So he used to catch Dizzy Dean.
And of course he was the first lieutenant and by then he'd probably been in the Army 10 or 12 years.
Lloyd Garrison was a captain, and he'd probably been in the army 20 years.
And Colonel Beasley was a lieutenant colonel, and he'd probably been in the army 25 years, so they sure didn't have very much rank.
Vinny Heiser used to say to his ROTC classes as well,
Everybody on campus ranks me except Lieutenant Moses and he's adjutant, he tells me what to do also.
What did these men teach you besides military life or artillery, your profession?
Well, I think they were demanding people and when we went out to drill, whatever, they set high standards and demanded compliance.
No question that they had tremendous influence on my life, on the standards that I'd set.
I'd do whatever I could to find favor with these people because I admired them a lot.
But they were certainly an inspiration.
And if you had to answer the question, in what ways do you think that the Corps helped or hindered your career, that would be part of it.
Oh, certainly.
There's no question that I had very fine experiences, received some recognition and inspiration from what I did in the Corps of Cadets at Texas A&M.
You were a regimental commander in 1938, 1939.
How'd you get that job, and can you explain your functions and duties?
Well, I guess
Through academic record and through accomplishments in ROTC, I was selected for the position of regimental commander.
What accomplishments in ROTC?
Well, the grades you made in military science.
and performance at the ROTC camp between your junior and senior year selection weren't made until after that.
There was a rotation of leadership in ROTC camp observation.
The same instructors were there at ROTC camp.
Texas Aggies were thrown in with cadets from other institutions too.
So there was an opportunity to express leadership capabilities in the rotational duties in ROTC camp.
What duties did you have as a commander?
Well as commander of the artillery regiment, which was composed of three battalions, two that lived on campus
And a day student battalion, I believe it amounted to some 3,000 cadets, I think, you know, the artillery raid cadets.
Really?
You were in charge of 3,000 cadets?
Was a good deal larger than, I think it was about 2,000 cadets.
Yeah, 2,000 cadets.
So anyway...
The military outfits, the ROTC companies and batteries were much larger than the ones today because ROTC was compulsory.
Everybody had to take at least two years and even if students were not enrolled in advanced ROTC, they still lived in the military outfits, wore the uniform, marched to meals.
their student life was all in ROTC units.
So there were some 2,000 cadets in there, and our duties during regular student living were to establish contact with the staff, with the company, with the battery commanders and artillery.
to command the unit during the two-hour drill periods each week.
In most cases, the activities were by batteries or platoons.
But in some cases, at ceremonies, for instance, reviews or whatever, we functioned as an entire regiment.
And of course, every meal, the unit formed up and marched the meals.
The staff fell in with the regimental commander.
There was a battalion staff for each battalion, marched the meals every three times a day, except on weekends since we didn't do it then.
Why were you picked as the regimental commander?
Well I don't know entirely.
At this time and every other time that I've gotten a promotion in my life I could always see there were a lot of people that appeared to be equally qualified and so you know I just don't know.
the officers to select me over a bunch of apparently equally qualified people.
But I was mighty proud to be selected.
I bet you were.
That's a great position for a man, what 20 years old were you at that time?
Yes, I was 20.
20 years old and you were in charge of basically 2,000 cadets?
Well, to the extent that a cadet officer was in charge.
At that time, I would have to say that the students have a lot more authority and responsibility today than we did then.
The ROTC instructors
were much more closely associated with us and we didn't expect to be given as much responsibility as young people expect today.
So I wouldn't say that we were making any great decisions about things.
What are your feelings on the fact that students have more responsibilities today or demand more responsibilities?
Do you think that's positive or negative?
I think it's very positive.
There's no question in my mind that the young people that come to Texas A&M today are far more qualified than I was in my day.
They're far better educated on arrival.
They're far more competent.
They expect and discharge responsibility better than we did.
And I'm mighty proud of the developments in student government and the responsibilities that students have.
Now, what were your feelings?
I want to talk about the ROTC camp.
Tell me about the ROTC camp, and tell me about the other corpsmen from other colleges.
Let's take time out for a minute.
Okay, time out.
